  # Colored Messages And Gradients

  ## Summary

  - Use Matrix org.matrix.custom.html for compatibility: plain body remains normal, so unsupported clients display
    regular text.
  - Solid colors use the Matrix-supported span data-mx-color="#rrggbb" path. Matrix spec v1.18 explicitly allows data-mx-
    color on span and says clients translate it to CSS.
  - Gradients use a client-specific span attribute, because Matrix only standardizes single hex colors, not gradients.
    Other clients should strip/ignore the attribute and show normal text.
  - Add a Tweaks setting, on by default, that disables both composing and rendering colored messages when off.
  - Enable the WYSIWYG composer by default while preserving existing user/account overrides.

  ## Key Changes

  - Add account data event com.elementcreations.message_style:

    {
      "version": 1,
      "defaultStyle": null
    }
     may be:

    { kind: "solid"; color: "#rrggbb" }
    { kind: "gradient"; direction: "left-to-right" | "top-to-bottom" | "diagonal-down" | "diagonal-up"; stops: { color:
"#rrggbb"; position: number }[] }
    Validate colors as 6-digit hex, gradient stops as 2-5 entries, and positions as 0..1.

    Validate colors as 6-digit hex, gradient stops as 2-5 entries, and positions as 0..1.
  - Add settings:
      - Tweaks.enableColoredMessages, account-level, default true, shown in Tweaks.
      - Change default feature_wysiwyg_composer to enabled.
      - Change default rich composer mode to rich text enabled, without overwriting saved user choices.
  - Composer UI:
      - Add two compact buttons to the WYSIWYG formatting bar: text color for selected text, and default message style.
      - Picker supports solid color and gradient mode.
      - Gradient picker supports up to 5 stops and direction selector: left-to-right, top-to-bottom, diagonal-down,
        diagonal-up.
      - Manual selection color wraps only the selected range.
      - Default style applies to future outgoing formatted sends when no explicit whole-message/manual color is present.
  - Sending/rendering:
      - Solid color HTML: <span data-mx-color="#rrggbb">text</span>.
      - Gradient HTML: <span data-mx-gradient="encoded-v1-payload">text</span>.
      - Renderer sanitizes data-mx-gradient, validates the decoded payload, and applies safe CSS background-image,
        background-clip: text, and transparent text fill.
      - When Tweaks.enableColoredMessages is off, strip/ignore both data-mx-color and data-mx-gradient for display and
        hide composer controls.
      - Apply default style to text, /me, edits, and formatted captions where the send path supports formatted_body.

  ## Test Plan

  - Unit test message content creation:
      - plain body never contains color/gradient markup.
      - solid default emits valid data-mx-color.
      - gradient default emits client-specific gradient metadata.
      - edits put styled content into both edited content and m.new_content where applicable.
  - Unit test sanitizer/rendering:
      - valid gradients render.
      - invalid colors, too many stops, invalid positions, or unknown directions are stripped.
      - setting off displays uncolored text.
  - UI tests:
      - selecting text and applying solid color affects only selected text.
      - setting a default gradient persists to account data and is restored after reload.
      - disabling the tweak hides color controls.
  - Compatibility check:
      - send colored message and inspect raw event: body is readable plain text, format is org.matrix.custom.html.

  ## Assumptions

  - No MSC is needed for solid colors; the current Matrix HTML formatting spec already covers single text colors.
  - Gradients intentionally remain client-specific for v1.
  - Default gradient direction selector includes exactly four directions.
  - The first implementation targets the WYSIWYG composer path; legacy/basic composer gets no new color UI beyond
    preserving fallback sends.
  - Source reference: Matrix Client-Server API, m.room.message HTML formatting rules:
    https://spec.matrix.org/latest/client-server-api/#mroommessage-msgtypes
